Never throw shit at a fan.&nbsp; First of all, you don't want to use that fan after shit has been flung at it; second of all,&nbsp; you can't clean the fan...I mean, you could clean the fan, but you'd have to unscrew the cover and clean the fan blades unnecessary.&nbsp; 

For the longest time, I thought I was a werewolf.&nbsp; I'd go outside at night and howl at the moon repeatedly and people would yell at me.&nbsp; I thought I was so misunderstood.&nbsp; I mean, I'm a werewolf, howling at the moon as what werewolves do.&nbsp; Well, then the full moon came and...you guessed it...nothing happened.&nbsp; Turns out that I'm just a big asshole.

Don't you love when you're talking about something and you don't realize how disgusting it sounds until after you said it?&nbsp; Like you'll be talking to a friend and somehow the conversation ends with you saying "no, the quickest way to kill a person is to shoot them in the back of the head, it goes right to the brain that way....wait, what the fuck are we talking about?"&nbsp;&nbsp;

I only wish I never limited myself toward listening to one genre of music for a good part of my life.&nbsp; Over the past few years, I have found the good parts about hip hop, jazz, country, soul, funk, pop, etc...&nbsp; I think every genre has its bad and its good.&nbsp; I think that a lot of rock fans get disoriented over rap because they hear Nelly or Puff Daddy both of whom have dominated the airwaves over the past few years.&nbsp; However, that's like judging rock music because of Creed.&nbsp; There's so much more there.&nbsp; Why dismiss metal because of Papa Roach?&nbsp; You know?&nbsp; Every classification of music has its high points and low points.&nbsp; I think it's silly to dismiss something entirely because of a shit band/group you heard once on the radio.&nbsp; Once you fully immerse yourself into it, you will realize that there are some really good shit that you're missing.&nbsp; Country, for example, all the shit that's been released in the past 20 years hasn't been too good, but you listen to the old school Country music like Johnny Cash...there is good country.&nbsp; And there is Alternative Country which has less of that slide guitar which, I think, is what throws me off.&nbsp; That and the distinctive Southern accent.&nbsp; Somebody like Whiskeytown came around in the late 90s and were basically all about Country, but because Ryan Adams had a different type of voice...a very smooth, rock-like voice and he wrote meaningful, poignant lyrics...it really showed me a new way of making that kind of music.&nbsp; Same thing with blues and jazz.&nbsp; Although, Jazz I do have a hard time with even though I do enjoy it.&nbsp; I just can only enjoy it in small doses; however, Miles Davis' "Bitches Brew" is a fantastic record.&nbsp; Well, fuck.&nbsp; Right?&nbsp; Even soul.&nbsp; I like soul.&nbsp; You know what?&nbsp; I like Marvin Gaye.&nbsp; I'm not ashamed of it and I don't think anybody should.&nbsp; I'd like to make a compilation cd of Marvin Gaye, Miles Davis, Johnny Cash, Public Enemy, Slayer, Sonic Youth, Michael Jackson, Funkadelic, and Fatboy Slim combined.&nbsp; It's all music.&nbsp; All music is enjoyable.&nbsp; Why limit yourself?&nbsp; There's so much out there?&nbsp; Why corner your musical tastes?&nbsp; I think that we only use 10% of our brain voluntarily.&nbsp; I think we can be open to other things if we tried to.&nbsp; There are things I've tried liking and didn't pan out, there are some thing that rubbed me the wrong way (Creed) from the beginning and I never wound up enjoying it.&nbsp; Some bands repulse me, some bands take me awhile to get into, some I love the first time I hear them.&nbsp; It all depends.&nbsp; I'm not saying I'm special because I am able to listen to Nas, Motorhead, Guns N Roses, and Rage Against the Machine interchangably...then add some Beatles and Sex Pistols in there...whatever.&nbsp; It may not be your bag.&nbsp; But don't dismiss it without opening up.&nbsp; "I tried listening to Illmatic and I couldn't understand anything so I turned it off."&nbsp; Yeah, ok.&nbsp; 

I'm starting to resent fashion being synonomous with music.&nbsp; You think of a band, you think of the fashion.&nbsp; I don't have to wear a Roc-A-Wear shirt in order to buy a Jay-Z album as I don't need to wear dark-rimmed glasses in order to appreciate (one of the better) emo bands.&nbsp; I think it's ok to follow a trend, as long as you are aware that it's a trend.&nbsp; However, I scoff at the idea of my fashion not being suitable enough for the type of music I listen to.&nbsp; I don't look like a guy who would like heavy metal?&nbsp; Because I don't wear a shirt with a heavy metal band on it?&nbsp; I don't think I need to express my tastes by merchandise except for cds.&nbsp; I do own shirts with band names on it, but I'd only wear it out of tribute or respect.&nbsp; Not because I want people to think I'm cool for listening to them.&nbsp; I just think Black Flag needs to be paid attention to sometimes.&nbsp; My point is that I'll wear what I want.&nbsp; And I do care about what people think sometimes so I won't go out of my way to dress like a jackass.&nbsp; I don't like drawing attention to myself.&nbsp; I don't like that unless I'm trying to make a statement which I rarely am.&nbsp; My statement is "I'll wear whatever the fuck I want."&nbsp; 

God I'm so cool.&nbsp; If I was ever in a band, I would encourage my fans not to buy the clothes that I wear because I'm wearing them.&nbsp; And I would only sell self-promoting merchandise at shows or something like that.&nbsp; I don't want some corporation handling my shit.&nbsp; If you like my band, you wanna wear a shirt that says so, come to a show.&nbsp; Or, order it exclusively off my website.&nbsp; I want ALL profit.&nbsp; MONEY IS GOD.&nbsp; Hahahahahahaha.&nbsp; And on that note, I'll end this here.&nbsp; Anyway, I hope all my points have been made.

No band pisses me off more than She Wants Revenge nowadays.&nbsp; Sure we have our Panic At the Discos, Fall Out Boys, Taking Back Sundays nowadays annoying the radiowaves.&nbsp; Jesus Christ how can you not gripe in pain hearing 'DON'T YOU EVER GET TOO FAR FROM ME"...SHUT THE FUCK UP.&nbsp; Dear god.&nbsp; Give me a fucking break!&nbsp; I guess I don't have that much problem with Fall Out Boy or Panic at the Disco except that they just sound like generic "emo" to me.&nbsp; What?&nbsp; One of them occasionally has electronic beats in their songs?&nbsp; Maybe a piano?&nbsp; Sweet dude, sweet.&nbsp; Go ahead, keep playing your game of denial.&nbsp; This phase, this fad will die soon.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I know because I was part of the Nu-Metal fad, but the difference is that I was 14 YEARS OLD.&nbsp; You 20 year old Taking Back Sunday fans are scaring me.&nbsp; 

None of that compares to the incredibly irritating monotone voice of the She Wants Revenge's lead singer.&nbsp; Dear god.&nbsp; What the fuck is the deal here?&nbsp; So, it's ok to rip off another band as long as you wait 20 years?&nbsp; It's not that they've been inspired by Joy Division, it's that they've completely ripped them off.&nbsp; From the beats to the Ian Curtis wannabe...the only difference is that Ian Curtis was legitimately depressed and suffered from epilepsy and he hated himself AND he was a fantastic songwriter.&nbsp; These guys (She Wants Revenge) do not have an ounce of creativity, originality, or ingenuity in their bones.&nbsp; One main difference is that while Joy Division's strength was Ian Curtis's highly literate and imaginative lyrics...She Wants Revenge seriously lacks that.&nbsp; Why settle for the imitators?&nbsp; If you seriously like She Wants Revenge, check out Joy Division and you'll feel like a fool.&nbsp; I'm sorry, but I'm just tired of the Joy Division imitators.&nbsp; I think the Editors, She Wants Revenge, The Killers (to some extent), and Interpol seriously owe their success to Joy Division and especially Ian Curtis.&nbsp; At least Interpol isn't a total ripoff, they actually know how to write good songs.&nbsp; The others?&nbsp; No.&nbsp; I don't mean to rag on the fans of these bands, you can like them.&nbsp; But, dear god, She Wants Revenge is terrible.&nbsp; 

I'm not just ragging on mainstream radio, it's just that most of it is bad.&nbsp; Almost all of it is bad.&nbsp; I would tell you when I think it's good.&nbsp; I like Franz Ferdinand, I supported Modest Mouse when they crossed over, I just get offended when I hear bands ripping off artists who perfected that sound over 25 years ago.&nbsp; Imitation may be the high form of flattery, but it's also annoying and unoriginal.&nbsp;
